 your passport</li>\n  <li>your previous medical certificate (if you have one)</li>\n  <li>your local doctor’s name, address and contact details</li>\n  <li>any medication you’re taking</li>\n  <li>your glasses or contact lenses (if you wear them)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>If you pass, your doctor will immediately issue you with an ENG1 certificate.</p>\n\n<h3>Fees</h3>\n\n<p>The maximum fee for an ENG1 medical examination is £80.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>Some <a href=\"http://www.dft.gov.uk/mca/mcga07-home/shipsandcargoes/mcga-shipsregsandguidance/marinenotices/mcga-mnotice.htm?textobjid=23913ED770CA6649\" title=\"Seafarer Medical Certificates accepted as equivalent to the UK Seafarer Medical Certificate (ENG1)\" rel=\"external\">seafarer medical certificates from other countries</a> are accepted instead of an ENG1 form.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>ML5 medical certificate</h2>\n\n<p>You need an ML5 medical certificate if any of the following apply, you&rsquo;re:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>in charge of a small commercial vessel</li>\n  <li>serving onboard a seagoing ship</li>\n  <li>the master of a passenger ship that doesn&rsquo;t go to sea (Class IV or V) </li>\n  <li>the master of a commercial vessel that doesn&rsquo;t go to sea </li>\n  <li>the master or a crew member of a small commercial vessel certificated for Area Category 2 to 6 (no more than 60 miles from a safe haven) </li>\n  <li>a crew member or anyone else (eg catering staff) who normally works on a domestic passenger ship (Class VI or VIA) that doesn&rsquo;t go to sea </li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>An ML5 certificate can be approved by any doctor who is registered with the General Medical Council and holds a current licence to practice.</p>\n\n<p>For more detailed information, download &lsquo;Medical fitness requirements for those working on domestic vessels and small commercial vessels&rsquo;.</p>\n\n<div class=\"form-download\">\n<p><a href=\"http://www.dft.gov.uk/mca/your_health_at_sea_6.pdf\" title=\"Download 'Medical fitness requirements for those working on domestic vessels and small commercial vessels' (PDF, 5.58MB)\" rel=\"external\">Download ‘Medical fitness requirements for those working on domestic vessels and small commercial vessels’ (PDF, 5.58MB)</a></p>\n</div>\n\n<h3>How to apply</h3>\n\n<p>Download the form below and take it to your local doctor to complete.</p>\n\n<div class=\"form-download\">\n<p><a href=\"https://afrmmcanet.mcga.gov.uk/formspublic/MSF4112.pdf\" title=\"Download 'Seafarer medical report form (ML5) and ML5 certificate' (PDF, 255KB)\" rel=\"external\">Download ‘Seafarer medical report form (ML5) and ML5 certificate’ (PDF, 255KB)</a></p>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Fees</h3>\n\n<p>The fee for an ML5 form isn’t set by the <abbr title=\"Maritime and Coastguard Agency\">MCA</abbr>, but your doctor will probably charge a fee for completing this.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>You may be allowed to work without a medical certificate for up to 3 months or until the next port of call, as long as you can get a valid certificate when you dock.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Suspension and cancellation of a medical fitness certificate</h2>\n\n<p>You can have your medical certificate suspended or cancelled if:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>there’s been a major change in your fitness</li>\n  <li>you don’t follow the terms of the certificate you’ve been issued with</li>\n  <li>the issuing doctor didn’t have full details of your condition at the time of examination</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice help-notice\">\n<p>You must hold a valid medical fitness certificate and produce this on demand to the right authorities.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>More information</h2>\n\n<p>Get more information on <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.dft.gov.uk/mca/mcga07-home/workingatsea/mcga-healthandsafety/mcga-medicalcertandadvice.htm\" title=\"seafarer medical certification and advice\">seafarer medical certificates</a> on the <abbr title=\"Maritime and Coastguar