h2>\n\n<p>Until the Maritime Labour Convention (<abbr title=\"Maritime Labour Convention\">MLC</abbr>) becomes part of UK law, the minimum age for seafarers is 16, although this is 18 if the work involves any:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>night work</li>\n  <li>hazardous tasks</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Hazardous tasks</h3>\n\n<p>Manual tasks on a ship can be hazardous if not done properly, like: </p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>lifting</li>\n  <li>hauling</li>\n  <li>mooring</li>\n  <li>towing </li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Employers of seafarers must ensure their staff:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>know how to operate any equipment correctly</li>\n  <li>are aware of safety procedures</li>\n  <li>have access to <a href=\"/health-and-safety-on-ships/protective-equipment\" title=\"Health and safety on ships: Protective personal equipment\">protective personal equipment</a> if needed</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Medical certification for seafarers</h2>\n\n<p>Anyone in charge of a ship must have an <a href=\"/seafarer-medical-certificates\" title=\"Seafarer medical certificates\">ENG1 seafarer medical certificate</a>.</p>\n\n<p>Other seafarers only need an <a href=\"/seafarer-medical-certificates\" title=\"Seafarer medical certificates\">ML5 medical certificate</a> if they’re working on a seagoing ship.</p>\n\n<p>Until the UK makes the <a href=\"/seafarer-working-and-living-rights/maritime-labour-convention\" title=\"Seafarer working and living conditions: Maritime labour convention\"><abbr title=\"Maritime Labour Convention\">MLC</abbr></a> law, seafarers&rsquo; employment agreements are covered by:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1995/21/section/25\" title=\"Read about seafarer employment agreement regulations in the Merchant Shipping Act 1995\">Merchant Shipping Act 1995</a></li>\n  <li><a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/1991/2144/contents/made\" title=\"Read the full text of the Merchant Shipping (Crew Agreements, Lists of Crew and Discharge of Seamen) Regulations 1991\">Merchant Shipping Regulations 1991</a></li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Certificates of competency</h2>\n\n<p>Some seafarers will need a <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.dft.gov.uk/mca/mcga07-home/workingatsea/mcga-trainingandcert.htm\" title=\"seafarer training and certification\">certificate of competency</a> before they can carry out certain duties.</p>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/seafarer-working-and-living-rights/conditions-of-employment","slug":"conditions-of-employment","order":3,"title":"Conditions of employment","body":"<p>Until the UK makes the <a href=\"/seafarer-working-and-living-rights/maritime-labour-convention\" title=\"Seafarer working and living rights: Maritime labour convention\">Maritime Labour Convention (<abbr title=\"Maritime Labour Convention\">MLC</abbr>) 2006</a> law, seafarers&rsquo; employment contracts are covered by:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1995/21/section/25\" title=\"Read about seafarer employment agreement regulations in the Merchant Shipping Act 1995\">Merchant Shipping Act 1995</a></li>\n  <li><a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/1991/2144/contents/made\" title=\"Read the full text of the Merchant Shipping (Crew Agreements, Lists of Crew and Discharge of Seamen) Regulations 1991\">Merchant Shipping Regulations 1991</a></li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Working time regulations</h2>\n\n<p>All <a href=\"/seafarer-working-and-living-rights/overview\" title=\"definition of seafarer\">seafarers</a> on seagoing ships are entitled to:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>a minimum of 10 hours&rsquo; rest in any 24 hour period</li>\n  <li>77 hours rest in any 7 day period</li>\n  <li>at least 4 weeks paid annual leave</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Read the <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2002/2125/contents/made\" title=\"Merchant Shipping (Hours of Work) Regulations 2002\">Merchant Shipping Regulations 2002</a> for more information.</p>\n\n<h2>Compensation</h2>\n\n<p>Seafarers must receive an &lsquo;onboard payment&rsquo; from their employer before they go to sea, in case the ship they&rsquo;re working on becomes unusable.</p>\n\n<p>This payment must be at the same level as a seafarer&rsquo;s normal wages, but can be limited to 2 months.</p>\n\n<p>Read more the <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1995/21/part/III/crossheading/relief-and-repatriation-and-relief-costs\" title=\"Merchant Shipping Act 1995\">Merchant Shipping Act 1995</a> for more information.</p>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/seafarer-working-and-living-rights/the-human-element","slug":"the-human-element","order":4,"title":"The 'human element'","body":"<p>The term &lsquo;human element&rsquo; covers anything to do with the interaction between a human and any system aboard ship, and is of high importance in maritime safety and security. </p>\n\n<p>Factors which affect the human element include:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>recruitment and selection policies and methods</li>\n  <li>crew competence, training and experience </li>\n  <li>conditions of service, motivation and morale</li>\n  <li>design, construction and ergonomics</li>\n  <li>standards of build and certification</li>\n  <li>maintenance</li>\n  <li>stress and fatigue</li>\n  <li>security</li>\n  <li>living and working conditions</li>\n  <li>manning levels and hours of work</li>\n  <li>management policies </li>\n  <li>safety management systems</li>\n  <li>operational systems</li>\n  <li>organisational and safety culture</li>\n  <li>culture of continuous improvement and workforce engagement </li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>For more information read  <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.dft.gov.uk/mca/mcga07-home/workingatsea/mcga-healthandsafety/mcga-adviceandguidance/mcga-ds-rap-he/mcga-ds-ssh-human-element.htm\" title=\"The human element: a guide to human behaviour in the shipping industry\">&lsquo;The human element: a guide to human behaviour in the shipping industry&rsquo;</a> 