Download ‘Marine Guidance Note (MGN) 399, Prevention of infectious disease at sea by immunisations and anti-malaria medication’ (PDF, 327KB)</a></p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"form-download\">\n<p><a href=\"http://www.dft.gov.uk/mca/mgn0038.pdf\" title=\"Download 'MGN 38 (M+F) Contamination of shttp://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1995/21/part/IV/crossheading/safety-and-health-on-shipships' air conditioning systems by Legionella Bacteria' (PDF, 183KB)\" rel=\"external\">Download ‘MGN 38 (M+F) Contamination of ships’ air conditioning systems by Legionella Bacteria’ (PDF, 183KB)</a></p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"form-download\">\n<p><a href=\"http://www.dft.gov.uk/mca/mcga-shs_capt_guide_chap6.pdf\" title=\"Download 'Communicable diseases information' (PDF, 90KB)\" rel=\"external\">Download ‘Communicable diseases’ (PDF, 90KB)</a></p>\n</div>\n\n<p>Until the UK makes the <a href=\"/seafarer-working-and-living-rights/maritime-labour-convention\" title=\"Maritime Labour Convention\">Maritime Labour Convention (MLA)</a> law, seafarers&rsquo; health and safety regulations are covered by the <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1995/21/part/IV/crossheading/safety-and-health-on-ships\" title=\"Merchant Shipping Act 1995: Safety and health on ships\">Merchant Shipping Act 1995</a></p>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/seafarer-working-and-living-rights/maritime-labour-convention","slug":"maritime-labour-convention","order":10,"title":"Maritime Labour Convention","body":"<p>The Maritime Labour Convention (<abbr title=\"Maritime Labour Convention\">MLC</abbr>) becomes UK law on 20 Aug 2013 and sets out the minimum working and living rights for seafarers.</p>\n\n<p>The Maritime and Coastguard Agency (<abbr title=\"Maritime and Coastguard Authority\">MCA</abbr>) has produced <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.dft.gov.uk/mca/mcga07-home/workingatsea/mcga-healthandsafety/maritime_labour_convention_2006/ds-ssh-mlc-dmlc.htm\" title=\"Maritime Labour Convention, 2006: Draft proposals\">draft proposals</a> for how employers and seafarers can prepare to meet the <abbr title=\"Maritime Labour Convention\">MLC</abbr>.</p>\n\n<h2>Exemptions</h2>\n\n<p>The <abbr title=\"Maritime Labour Convention\">MLC</abbr> doesn’t cover seafarers serving on the following boats:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>ships navigating inland or sheltered waters subject to port regulations</li>\n  <li>fishing vessels</li>\n  <li>warships and naval auxiliaries</li>\n  <li>traditional ships, such as dhows</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Minimum requirements</h2>\n\n<p>The <abbr title=\"Maritime Labour Convention\">MLC</abbr> sets out minimum standards for seafarers to work on a ship, including:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>minimum age</li>\n  <li>medical certification</li>\n  <li>training and qualifications</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Age</h2>\n\n<p>The minimum age for seafarers will be 16, though night workers have to be 18 or over.</p>\n\n<p>Exceptions to these provisions can be allowed for:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>training purposes</li>\n  <li>where the seafarer&rsquo;s duties require it, as long as their <a href=\"/health-and-safety-on-ships/overview\" title=\"Health and safety on ships: Overview\">health and safety</a> isn’t affected</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Medical certification</h2>\n\n<p>All seafarers must have the right <a href=\"/seafarer-medical-certificates\" title=\"Seafarer medical certificates\">medical certificate</a> to work at sea before they can work on ships.</p>\n\n<h2>Training and qualifications</h2>\n\n<p>Under the <abbr title=\"Maritime Labour Convention\">MLC</abbr>, seafarers will need to:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>be trained and qualified to perform onboard duties</li>\n  <li>receive personal safety training</li>\n  <li>for training to conform to <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.ilo.org/global/standards/maritime-labour-convention/lang--en/index.htm\" title=\"Maritime Labour Convention\">International Maritime Organisation standards</a></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Find out more about seafarer <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.dft.gov.uk/mca/mcga07-home/workingatsea/mcga-trainingandcert.htm\" title=\"Training and certification\">training and qualifications</a> on the <abbr title=\"Maritime and Coastguard Authority\">MCA</abbr> website.</p>\n\n<h2>Conditions of employment</h2>\n\n<p>Under the <abbr title=\"Maritime Labour Convention\">MLC</abbr>, seafarers will have minimum working rights covering:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>employment agreements</li>\n  <li>wages</li>\n  <li>hours of work and rest</li>\n  <li>entitlement to leave</li>\n  <li>repatriation</li>\n  <li>compensation for a ship&rsquo;s loss or foundering</li>\n  <li>manning levels</li>\n  <li>career and skills development</li>\n  <li>employment opportunities</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Employment contracts</h2>\n\n<p>The convention makes sure contracts between seafarers and employers provide fair living and working conditions.</p>\n\n<p>Contracts should be in written or translated into English and include:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>employer&rsquo;s name and address</li>\n  <li>seafarer&rsquo;s name, date and place of birth</li>\n  <li>place and date where agreement signed</li>\n  <li>conditions for the termination of agreement</li>\n  <li>health and social security protection benefits provided by employer</li>\n  <li>seafarer&rsquo;s right to repatriation</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Seafarers must also be:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>allowed to read and consider contracts before signing them</li>\n  <li>given a record of their employment</li>\n  <li>given their own copy of their contract (the employer should also have a copy)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Wages</h2>\n\n<p>Under the <abbr title=\"Maritime Labour Convention\">MLC</abbr>, seafarers wages will be:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>paid regularly, ie weekly or monthly</li>\n  <li>include monthly statements of accounts</li>\n  <li>allow seafarers to transfer part or all of their wages</li>\n  <li>keep currency conversion charges to reasonable limits</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Hours of work and rest</h2>\n\n<p>Seafarers don’t have to work more than:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>14 hours in any 24 hour period</li>\n  <li>72 hours in any 7 day period</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Hours of rest must be at least:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>10 hours in any 24 hour period</li>\n  <li>77 hours in any 7 day period</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Crew exercises, eg lifeboat drills, must cause minimal disruption to seafarers rest periods. After being on call, a seafarer is entitled to a rest period afterwards.</p>\n\n<div class=\"form-download\">\n<p><a href=\"http://www.dft.gov.uk/mca/mgn0088.pdf\" title=\"Download 'Marine Guidance Note (MGN) 88 (M+F) Implementation of EC Directive 94/33 Merchant Shipping and Fishing Vessels (Health and Safety at Work) (Employment of Young Persons) Regulations 1998' (PDF, 149KB)\" rel=\"external\">Download ‘Marine Guidance Note (MGN) 88 Merchant Shipping and Fishing Vessels Regulations 1998’ (PDF, 149KB)</a></p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Holiday pay</h2>\n\n<p>Under the <abbr title=\"Maritime Labour Convention\">MLC</abbr>, seafarers will be entitled to paid leave calculated at 2.5 days per calendar month of employment.</p>\n\n<p>Read more about holiday pay for seafarers in the <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2002/2125/regulation/12/made\" title=\"Merchant Shipping Regulations (Hours of Work) 2002\">Merchant Shipping Regulations 2002.</a></p>\n\n<h2>Repatriation</h2>\n\n<p>This gives seafarers the right to be returned to their home country:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>when their employment contract ends or is cancelled</li>\n  <li>when they’re no longer able to carry out their duties</li>\n  <li>in the event of shipwreck</li>\n  <li>in a ship bound for a war zone they haven’t agreed to go</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Employers cannot request advance payment for repatriation from seafarers in part or full. If an employer doesn’t make repatriation arrangements, seafarers can be repatriated by the <abbr title=\"Maritime and Coastguard Authority\">MCA</abbr>.</p>\n\n<h2>Accommodation and recreational facilities</h2>\n\n<p>The Maritime and Labour Convention (<abbr title=\"Maritime Labour Convention\">MLC</abbr>) will make sure seafarers have access to fair accommodation and recreational facilities when living on ships.</p>\n\n<p>Passenger or special purpose ships weighing 3,000 gross tonnes or more must follow the <abbr title=\"Maritime Labour Convention\">MLC</abbr> and provide accommodation and living areas for seafarers that offer:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>separate berths with sufficient headroom</li>\n  <li>safe location of sleeping rooms, eg not forward of collision bulkheads</li>\n  <li>storage for personal effects, eg lockers</li>\n  <li>drying machines (for laundry)</li>\n  <li>reduced risk of exposure to hazards, eg noise or chemicals</li>\n  <li>an adequate number of hospital berths</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>This only applies to vessels built on or after the date the <abbr title=\"Maritime Labour Convention\">MLC</abbr> was adopted in the relevant country.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Health protection and medical care</h2>\n\n<p>The <abbr title=\"Maritime Labour Convention\">MLC</abbr> sets minimum requirements for:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>medical care, on board ship and ashore</li>\n  <li>health and safety protection</li>\n  <li>accident prevention</li>\n  <li>employer&rsquo;s liability</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Medical care</h2>\n\n<p>These will cover seafarers rights to:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>fair on board health protection facilities, including dental care</li>\n  <li>the right to visit qualified medical personnel while in port</li>\n  <li>access to a qualified medical doctor on ships carrying more than 100 people on international voyages lasting more than 3 days</li>\n  <li>where there is no doctor on board, there must be designated and able seafarer(s) to provide first aid and medical care</li>\n  <li>protection from hazardous cargoes</li>\n  <li>proper medical record keeping</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Employer’s liabilities</h2>\n\n<p>Under the <abbr title=\"Maritime Labour Convention\">MLC</abbr>, if a seafarer suffers accident or disability because of their work the employer must provide where necessary:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>assistance and medical care</li>\n  <li>financial assistance for long-term disability or illness</li>\n  <li>repatriation</li>\n  <li>burial</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>If an injury isn’t related to a seafarer’s duties or was caused by wilful misconduct, an employer isn’t liable for this.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Health and safety protection</h2>\n\n<p>Under the <abbr title=\"Maritime Labour Convention\">MLC</abbr>, seafarers work environments on ships must:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>have regular risk assessments of workplace hazards, eg from machinery</li>\n  <li>take steps to prevent work accidents</li>\n  <li>have a system for reporting accidents</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Enforcement</h2>\n\n<p>Under the <abbr title=\"Maritime Labour Convention\">MLC</abbr>, the <abbr title=\"Maritime and Coastguard Authority\">MCA</abbr> can withdraw a ship’s maritime labour certificate if seafarer living and working conditions are breached.</p>\n\n"}]},"tags":[{"title":"Maritime vessels and work at sea","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/business%2Fmaritime.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":"Includes health and safety onboard, crew, registering vessels","short_description":null,"type":"section"},"content_with_tag":{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/with_tag.json?tag=business%2Fmaritime","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/browse/business/maritime"},"parent":{"title":"Businesses and self-employed","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/business.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":"Information about starting up and running a business in the UK, including help if you're self employed or a sole trader.","short_description":null,"type":"section"},"content_with_tag":{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/with_tag.json?tag=business","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/browse/busines